Networking today
1. It Affect our lives
	a. Importance: it is vital as air, water, food and shelter. It connects people, devices, business or organization globally.
	b. Global Connectivity: It enhanced the social interaction, education, entertainment, collaboration and all at the palm of your hand. (ex. Viber, Netflix,etc)

2. Network Components
	a. Host Roles - are any device that communicates over the network.
		Types of Hosts:
      2.a Servers - provides services like Email server: Handles email communication.
      2.b Clients - resquests services from servers like
  b. Peer-to-peer Networks - Devices that can act as server and a client. It is simple and effective for a small networks.
  c. End devices - These devices where messages originate or terminate (Ex. CPs, IoT devices, Laptop, etc.)
  d. Intermediary Devices - responsible for forwardting and routing the data, maintaining error and status notification. (Example: Switches, Routers, Firewalls)
  e. Network Media:
      2.a Copper Wires - transmit data thru electrical pulses
      2.b Fiber Optic - Uses light pulses for data transmission.
      2.c Wireless - use electromagnetic waves

3. Network Representations and Topologies
  a. Network Diagrams - Visual Representaiton od devices and connections.
      3.a NIC (Network Interface Card) - Device hardware for connectivity
      3.b Physical Port - Device hardware interface
      3.c Interface - Term used interchangeably with "Port"
  b. Topology Diagrams
      3.a Physical Topology - Physical placement of Devices
      3.b Logical Topology - Data flow addressing and configurations.

4. Common types of networks
  a. Network by size
      4.a Small home networks - Few interconnected devices
      4.b SOHO - Small Office/Home Office
      4.c LANs and WANs - Hundreds or thousands of devices accross locations
      4.d World Wide Networks - Millions of interconnected devices globally
  b. LANs and WANs
      4.a LAN (Local Area Network) - Limited to small geographical areas (Offices, schools)
      4.b WAN (Wide Area Network) - Connect multiple LANs over large distances and typically managed by services providers
  c. The Internet - Global Interconnection od LANs and WANs (Maintained by orgs: IETF, ICANN, IAB)
  D. Intranet and Extranet: 
      4.a Intranets - Private networks for internal organizational use
      4.b Extranet - Secure network access for external users or organizations.

5. Internet Connecttions 
  a. Home and Small Office
      5.a Cable: High Speed, always-on connection via TV service providers.
      5.b DSL: High-speed over phone lines.
      5.c Cellular: Internet via mobile networks
      5.d Satellite: Suitable for rural/remotes areas
      5.e Dial-up: Low-speed, outdated technology
  b. Business Connections
      5.a Leased Lines - Dedicated circuits for private connections.
      5.b Ethernet WAN - Extends LAN capabilities over wide areas
      5.c DSL Variants - Includes business-class DSL
      5.d Satellite - Alternative for locations without wired access.
  c. Converged Networks - Unified communications infrastructure for Data, Voice and video services.

6. Reliable Networks 
  a. Fault Tolerence - Redundancy using multiple pathways ensures reliability / can do packet switching that enable alternate routing during failures
  b. Scalabiliy - Ability to grow the network without affective performance
  c. Quality of Services (QoS) - Prioritizes critical traffice like voice and video
  d. Security - Infrastructure Security for protecting Devices and Access | Information Security - Ensures CIA triad.

7. Network Trends
  a. BYOD (Bring Your Own Device) - Users bring personnal devices 
  b. Online Collaboration - tools like cisco webex
  c. Video communication - realtime video conference
  d. Cloud Computing - remote access to data and applications via cloud services.





